	<td class="alt1" id="td_post_917052">
	
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_917052">
                  
                  <a href="http://www.silkyvenom.com/forums/showthread.php?p=31380#post31380" target="_blank">Brad attempt to placate the angry Vanbois</a><br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				I have to respectfully disagree. There was a lot of information released at E3 and we've got some great coverage so far, and I expect to see a lot more over the next week.<br />
<br />
That said, please also understand that one of the things we are focusing on right now is getting the word out about Vanguard to people who do not regularly follow the game or perhaps haven't even heard about it at all or were before E3 not interested in the game.<br />
<br />
Those of you who follow Vanguard closely and have been for some time I can understand that it might be a little frustrating that our focus is less on getting you guys new info but more about getting the info about the game that is already known by avid followers of the game to those people who are not avid followers in the hope that they too will become interested and excited about the game.<br />
<br />
We've reached a lot of people through the grass-roots 'marketing' and PR and community building we've been doing for a couple of years now. Probably 70,000 to 100,000 people. I'm pretty proud of that, and also very appreciative and humbled by the existing Vanguard communities support and interest in the game. You guys have been extremely supportive, loyal, and patient. Again, thank you so much.<br />
<br />
But I also truly believe that while Vanguard isn't a game like WoW, designed to appeal to the ‘mass market’, hence their millions and millions of sales and subscribers, that is *is* a game that very conservatively will attract 250k-500k people, and more optimistically between 500k and a million. It may not be ‘mainstream’, but neither is it ‘niche’ either (regardless of the assertion that it is posting by skeptics here and there). But in order to accomplish that goal and to reach those people who we are confident will be interested in Vanguard, we now need to start getting the word out about the game through more mainstream ways -- solid E3s like we just wrapped up, magazine write-ups and covers (The CGM cover was great, but I am very confident we'll get more covers before release), by beginning to place advertisements about the game, both online and in gaming pubs, etc.<br />
<br />
We started this back in Jan/Feb and you've seen a lot of it, with probably the greatest accomplishment so far the CGM cover. But we need to keep going and be even more aggressive -- the PR blitz has begun, and the results have been good, but there's still a lot more to be done and to be accomplished if we are to reach out beyond the 70,000-100,000 people who already follow Vanguard closely.<br />
<br />
What this means, and I want to be totally up front with you all, is that much of the marketing and PR effort going forward is not going to be aimed at you guys. Please, please don't take that as any indication that we don't feel you are important; rather, please understand that for Vanguard to be the success we all want it to be, we need to now reach out in a more mainstream and conventional way. And what that means is that a lot of what you are going to read about in the more mainstream press (both online and in publications) is going to be stuff you guys already know about. You already know a LOT about the game, especially the core message about what Vanguard is all about, what we're trying to accomplish with it, who our target audience is (the core gamer), etc. But again, there are hundreds of thousands of people who don't know about Vanguard and we need to now reach out to them and make sure they know what you guys already know.<br />
<br />
Now that doesn't mean you will be ignored, or that new information about the game that hasn't been talked about at all won't be released, slowly but surely, between now and release. In fact, if you read the coverage we've already received from E3, or you were lucky enough to have been at E3 and seen the game yourselves and been able to meet our team and ask questions (which I hope you got answered), I think you will find that new and exciting information, even to those of you who already know so much about Vanguard, was indeed released I think you guys saw some pretty cool new stuff in the batch of screenshots that were released for E3, learned a lot more about our character customization engine, player housing, mounts, crafting, etc. We definitely even though we were focused on getting the message out to people who don't already follow the game closely wanted to get out some new info and screenshots showing things you haven't seen or heard about before. You also now have a movie that is fairly recent in terms of what it shows – I know it’s short and more of a teaser, and I know you guys want and deserve a more in-depth and longer in-game movie – and as I have posted, I think now, with SOE’s help, we will be able to get you that movie and more because they have the people and infrastructure we need to create such a movie without pulling a bunch of our own people away from making the game and creating such a movie ourselves.<br />
<br />
But please understand that while you will not be ignored, that those who are already following the game right now are not our focus because like I said: it's essential that we reach out to a lot more than 70-100k people between now and launch. I humbly ask that you put yourselves in our shoes and also see where I'm coming from -- that the success of Vanguard relies on us now using more conventional types of marketing and PR to reach beyond the community that already exists.<br />
<br />
I hope that makes sense -- if it doesn't, or if you disagree, please say so and I will try to clarify further and answer any questions or concerns. The main thing though is that I wanted to be straight up with you guys and manage your expectations. Bottom line: It doesn't make sense that the majority of our efforts now be focused on 'preaching to the choir', so to speak.<br />
<br />
Again, that by NO means doesn't mean that we don't feel you guys are important and deserve more information and attention. The opposite is rather true -- we are EXTREMELY grateful to all of you who have been following the game for some time, many of you from the very beginning. That we were able to reach out to you and get 70-100k people interested in this game with very little conventional marketing and PR shows the strength of Vanguard's appeal -- you guys are the foundation upon which we must now build. And that is so key, that we have a solid foundation of people already interested in the game upon which to build. That so many of you have created web sites, posted about the game, evangelized it, etc. has been crucial and priceless. You have my eternal gratitude and appreciation.<br />
<br />
That's why I'm posting this -- I would feel HORRIBLE if you guys felt that because now the majority of our efforts will be spent on getting the word out to even more people and in a more mainstream way, that you might feel neglected or unappreciated or forgotten. I promise you, that is absolutely not the case. That there is already 70-100k interested in the game through our efforts and building community, being active on the boards, supporting our affiliate web sites, and largely because of all of you posting and spreading the news, is fantastic and like I said, humbling -- we're truly blown away.<br />
<br />
I promise you all that even though our primary focus will now being on getting the word out to those who don't follow Vanguard regularly or who don't even know much or anything about the game at all, that we will continue to do everything we can do continue to support you, to give you guys new information about the game, to keep posting on the boards and responding to your questions or concerns. Quite frankly, you deserve it, along with our very real gratitude.<br />
<br />
But again, now we need to get the word out through more conventional marketing and PR means. Again, while perhaps Vanguard isn't the mainstream game that WoW is, and while we may not get millions and millions of subscribers, I also know in my heart and feel very strongly and bullish that there are a LOT more people for which Vanguard is the game for them. Again, I feel very confident that Vanguard is conservatively a 250-500k game, and then more optimistically at 500k-million subscriber game -- the game really, IMHO, has that potential. And it also needs to see those kinds of numbers for it to be at a success level such that it generates the revenue we need to do a great job post-release -- that we have enough revenue to support a large live team, a large expansion team, and a great customer service team. And, yes, we also want that level of success so that Sigil can become profitable, so that we can share that profit with our employees who have been working so hard for so long to build the game we all want and dream about.<br />
<br />
How will we find the time and resources to keeping building the game and get it out in a timely (yet not rushed manner), but also market the game to those 250k to one million or so people who we truly believe Vanguard is the game for them, and then also keep supporting all of you, our loyal community that again is the foundation upon which we will build upon? Well, it's going to be tough, but we're going to do whatever it takes to do just that. Our co-publishing relationship with SOE now also helps a GREAT deal. Whatever your feelings about SOE, they know how to get the word out, how to place ads, and are committed to helping us as much as possible in the more conventional marketing and PR that is now necessary to reach all of those other people.<br />
<br />
And with the way our deal is structured with them, we will be working *together* with them on this process, guiding this effort, approving ads and other marketing efforts. But also we will now be able to harness their marketing and PR engine and resources, which is something we previously lacked and one of the reasons we made this arguably radical change, moving from Microsoft to SOE, and at the same time raising the money such that we can now have even more influence and say relative to this effort. This is why I am so bullish that we can reach out to that many more people and attract the kinds of numbers I am talking about. Before this change, I was very concerned as to whether our publisher was ready and had the time to focus on what it takes to promote, launch, and host a AAA game like Vanguard. Now I am not worried at all. Now I know we have the time to not only make sure Vanguard, through beta feedback, through a longer beta, etc., but also a partner who has the know-how, experience, and resources to help us market this game and get it the attention and exposure it deserves. We can keep doing what we love to do (work on the game), but then not only harness SOE's expertise and significant PR and marketing team, but also work together with them and help guide them so that we will be able to get the word out to all of these other MMOG players for whom I am very confident Vanguard is made for and who should be part of the community that has already formed.<br />
<br />
Just look at the last year or so -- mainstream and more conventional marketing efforts should have already begun. Ads for Vanguard should already have been appearing in the various gaming pubs. Online advertisement on the big game sites also should already be in place. Look at how long before release other MMOGs are advertised in this manner -- look at the efforts to get the word out about WoW, Guildwars, D&amp;D Online, and even smaller games. Unfortunately, however, this hasn't been the case for Vanguard – these efforts have been sorely lacking. Like I said, it has gotten better since January or so -- we have received some previews and even got our first cover. What we have achieved, however, has largely been due to Sigil's effort, and to get it done we had to allocate resources at times that could/should have really been working on the game instead. And that's just not right – we shouldn’t be in a position where we have to choose from the valuable in-house resources we have and feel we need to sacrifice in one area (say development) in order to market the game. We need a co-publisher who understands that MMOGs need to be pushed early on, that ads need to be placed a good year before release, etc. And now we have one. And when I've talked about why we made such a big change, this aspect of it was a big part of it (along with getting the time we need to not be rushed out, as well as the hosting we need to be able to conduct a proper beta, bring in people when we need to, patch as often as we need to, etc.)<br />
<br />
Anyway, I've rambled a bit and covered a lot of topics in this post, although in a sense they are indeed all interrelated. But it was also something that I needed to say and communicate to all of you because you deserve to know why we have made the decisions we have made, and also know where our focus is going to be going forward and how we are prioritizing things. Let me know if this all makes sense -- I will watch this thread closely and do my best to answer any questions or concerns you have, as well as any additional clarity that you guys need such that you can understand why and where we are coming from, have made these major decisions and changes recently, and what our plans are going forward. Quite frankly, you guys deserve to know -- we have always been as open with you all as we could and made ourselves available to answer questions and provide clarity, and that’s not going to change. Again, we owe you all SO much for being a huge part in bringing Vanguard to where it is today. And now, as we continue to and also bolster and increase our efforts to get the word out about Vanguard, as some of our focus in this area changes and evolves, that last thing I want is any of you feeling is left out or feeling less important. Honestly, if you guys did end up feeling that way, I couldn’t sleep at night I would feel horrible. I've seen games where the initial community was supported up to a certain point, and then when the game was ready to go mainstream, that initial community abandoned or receive less attention. In those situations, whether intentionally or not, the initial community has been in a way 'used', or merely a tool. And, quite frankly, that's unacceptable and crap. Forgetting our roots, all of you who have been integral in getting us this far, etc. is not what Sigil is all about -- we won't forget, we won't stop supporting, and we won't stop listening, even with some of our priorities now needing to change.<br />
<br />
thanks all,
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>
                  
		</div>
