                  <div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Zruu</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">This <i>was</i> the final E3 before launch, though.</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>
<br />
Yeah, and the booths were umpteen times bigger and in good locations. And they have talked to way more peeps than before.<br />
<br />
And there have been much more info coming out now this soon, compared to the last E3.<br />
<br />
As I said in the SV forums, some people want to write up &quot;good&quot; presentations and ecode vids properly, watermark screenies, etc, instead of just posting a ZOMG I saw vanguard and here is a shitty picture of it.<br />
<br />
There is more info coming out after E3 than during it. If I was an affiliate writer, I would do the same. Write up a good presentation, etc, before posting.<br />
Last years E3 had articles coming out 3-4 weeks after the event.<br />
<br />
If people feel that &quot;OMG Vanguard is gonna fail because there is no new infos during E3 (other than the 5-6 gameplay videos and articles in many gaming places)&quot; then you might as well stop looking and realize that deep down you don't want to play it, and should just let it go. Nobody would blame them.<br />
<br />
If people follow the game so closely as to care what is and what is not shown on E3, then I would assume that they either<br />
a) Wished for the game to be great<br />
b) Are strange persons that for some reason wish for a mmorpg to fail for no reason other than fear of any other mmorpg than their desired one.<br />
<br />
If person A starts yelling, they need to get patience. The person B will cry out no matter what comes out. For the general public, what is displayed in the key magazines and sites will be what matters. And that will not come until a little bit (for mags a few weeks) after E3.<br />
<br />
Take WoW. That is a major success. I didn't follow it too much at all, and come their last E3 I saw nothing. Not because it wasn't there, I'm sure it was. I just did not pay attention. Meaning that if a game with closing in on 7 million subs could miss my &quot;gaming infos&quot; radar (I knew of it of course, but got more info from the WoW thread here at graffes than anywhere else), the n I see no reason why VG will fail for not hitting everyones radar at the last E3 either. Especially this soon after it.<br />
<br />
Not saying that I am comparing VG with WoW, just saying that just because a game isn't on the CNN front page the day after E3 does not mean that their E3 presentations were fubar and the game is dooooooooooomed. <br />
<br />
One thing I will never understand is people who follow games, be it news or lack of news, that they do not like. It seems like such a waste of time and efforts. Why hold feelings towards something they do not care about. I could care less about Tabula Rasa, and many other mmorpgs in development. But you don't see me on their threads or forums going &quot;ZOMG this sucks! You suck. This game will fail! DOOOMED! This game will never work!&quot;<br />
Negative critizism because the person wish the game to succeed, but do not like the direction it is heading, that is fine. But to go apeshit and such at games that have always headed in one direction, meaning the game is not for that person.... strange.
                  
		</div>
